"Pörtner H.O., Schulte P.M., Wood C.M., Schiemer F.","Niche dimensions in fishes: An integrative view",2010,"Physiological and Biochemical Zoology","83","5",,"808","826",,,10.1086/655977,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956052326&partnerID=40&md5=c922476a882af5ed8978b48dd40a3f78","Section Integrative Ecophysiology, Alfred-Wegener-Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bremerhaven D-27515, Germany; Department of Zoology, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada; Department of Biology, McMaster University, Hamilton, ON L8S 4K1, Canada; Department of Freshwater Ecology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, Vienna A1090, Austria","Pörtner, H.O., Section Integrative Ecophysiology, Alfred-Wegener-Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bremerhaven D-27515, Germany; Schulte, P.M., Department of Zoology, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada; Wood, C.M., Department of Biology, McMaster University, Hamilton, ON L8S 4K1, Canada; Schiemer, F., Department of Freshwater Ecology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, Vienna A1090, Austria","Current shifts in ecosystem composition and function emphasize the need for an understanding of the links between environmental factors and organism fitness and tolerance. The examples discussed here illustrate how recent progress in the field of comparative physiology may provide a better mechanistic understanding of the ecological concepts of the fundamental and realized niches and thus provide insights into the impacts of anthropogenic disturbance. Here we argue that, as a link between physiological and ecological indicators of organismal performance, the mechanisms shaping aerobic scope and passive tolerance set the dimensions of an animal's niche, here defined as its capacity to survive, grow, behave, and interact with other species. We demonstrate how comparative studies of cod or killifish populations in a latitudinal cline have unraveled mitochondrial mechanisms involved in establishing a species' niche, performance, and energy budget. Riverine fish exemplify how the performance windows of various developmental stages follow the dynamic regimes of both seasonal temperatures and river hydrodynamics, as synergistic challenges. Finally, studies of species in extreme environments, such as the tilapia of Lake Magadi, illustrate how on evolutionary timescales functional and morphological shifts can occur, associated with new specializations. We conclude that research on the processes and time course of adaptations suitable to overcome current niche limits is urgently needed to assess the resilience of species and ecosystems to human impact, including the challenges of global climate change. © 2010 by The University of Chicago. All rights reserved.",,"anthropogenic effect; bioenergetics; cichlid; climate change; cyprinid; ecosystem function; ecosystem resilience; environmental factor; fitness; gadoid; hydrodynamics; niche; physiological response; river system; seasonal variation; specialization; survival; tolerance; adaptation; animal; article; climate change; comparative study; ecology; ecosystem; energy metabolism; evolution; fish; mitochondrion; physiology; reproductive fitness; species difference; theoretical model; Adaptation, Biological; Animals; Biological Evolution; Climate Change; Ecology; Ecosystem; Energy Metabolism; Fishes; Genetic Fitness; Mitochondria; Models, Theoretical; Physiology, Comparative; Species Specificity; Kenya; Lake Magadi; Rift Valley; Animalia; Cyprinodontiformes; Cyprinodontoidei; Pisces; Tilapia",,,,,,"Able, K.W., Palmer, R.E., Salinity effects on fertilization success and larval mortality of Fundulus heteroclitus (1988) Copeia, 2, pp. 345-350; Adams, S.M., Lindmeier, J.B., Duvernell, D.D., Microsatellite analysis of the phylogeography, pleistocene history and secondary contact hypotheses for the killifish, Fundulus heteroclitus (2006) Mol Ecol, 15, pp. 1109-1123; Angiletta, M., (2009) Thermal Adapt